    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so im doing a lot of hiit lately and my legs feel like they are burning like crazy during the sprints. can u explain what is actually happening with the lactic acid in my muscles when that happens? and how does my body get rid of it after i stop?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the burning sensation in your legs during high-intensity interval training (HIIT) is a classic sign of lactic acid buildup. When you sprint, your muscles need more oxygen than your body can supply, so they switch to anaerobic respiration, which produces lactic acid as a byproduct. This lactic acid is what causes that burning feeling in your muscles. \n\nAfter you stop sprinting, your body begins to clear the lactic acid. It gets converted back into pyruvate, which can then be used for energy or sent to the liver to be turned into glucose. This process helps to reduce the lactic acid levels in your muscles and alleviate the burning sensation. It's a bit like a cleanup crew, working to restore order after a bit of chaos. So, while the burning might be uncomfortable, it's your body's way of telling you that it's working hard to keep you going!",
      "source": "target",
